    <div class="container">
        <header>
            <h1>Conducted and Radiated Media</h1>
            <p class="subtitle">Understanding the Foundations of Information Infrastructure</p>
            <div class="progress-bar">
                <div class="progress-fill" id="progressBar"></div>
            </div>
        </header>

        <section class="section">
            <div class="storytelling-intro">
                <strong>Imagine...</strong> you're an architect designing a city's communication network. Would you run cables through every building, or broadcast signals through the air? This fundamental choice between <em>conducted</em> and <em>radiated</em> media has shaped our entire digital infrastructure. Let's explore this fascinating journey together.
            </div>

            <h2>The Tale of Two Transmission Methods</h2>
            <p>In the realm of information infrastructure, we encounter two fundamental approaches to moving data from point A to point B. Like rivers and winds in nature, information flows through either <strong>conducted media</strong> (guided pathways) or <strong>radiated media</strong> (unguided propagation through space).</p>
            
            <div class="interactive-demo">
                <h3>Interactive Signal Visualization</h3>
                <p>Click the buttons below to see how signals behave in different media:</p>
                <button class="demo-button" onclick="showConductedSignal()">Conducted Signal</button>
                <button class="demo-button" onclick="showRadiatedSignal()">Radiated Signal</button>
                <button class="demo-button" onclick="resetVisualization()">Reset</button>
                
                <div class="signal-visualization" id="signalViz">
                    <div class="wave conducted-wave" id="conductedWave"></div>
                    <div class="wave radiated-wave" id="radiatedWave"></div>
                </div>
                <p id="signalDescription">Click a button above to see signal behavior</p>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section class="section">
            <h2>Conducted Media: The Guided Path</h2>
            <div class="storytelling-intro">
                Think of conducted media as <em>digital highways</em> ‚Äì structured pathways that guide information with precision and control. Just as a water pipe directs flow exactly where needed, conducted media channels data through physical conduits.
            </div>
            
            <div class="comparison-grid">
                <div class="comparison-card">
                    <h3>Physical Characteristics</h3>
                    <ul class="characteristics-list">
                        <li>Bounded transmission medium</li>
                        <li>Physical waveguide structure</li>
                        <li>Electromagnetic waves confined</li>
                        <li>Predictable signal propagation</li>
                        <li>Minimal external interference</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                
                <div class="comparison-card">
                    <h3>Performance Attributes</h3>
                    <ul class="characteristics-list">
                        <li>High bandwidth capacity</li>
                        <li>Low signal attenuation</li>
                        <li>Excellent security properties</li>
                        <li>Consistent transmission quality</li>
                        <li>Distance-dependent performance</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="real-world-examples">
                <h3>Real-World Applications</h3>
                <div class="example-card">
                    <strong>Fiber Optic Networks:</strong> The backbone of modern internet, using light pulses through glass fibers to achieve speeds up to 100 Gbps over thousands of kilometers.
                </div>
                <div class="example-card">
                    <strong>Coaxial Cable Systems:</strong> Cable television and broadband internet delivery, supporting multiple channels simultaneously through frequency division.
                </div>
                <div class="example-card">
                    <strong>Twisted Pair Cables:</strong> Ethernet networks in buildings, balancing cost-effectiveness with reliable data transmission for local area networks.
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section class="section">
            <h2>Radiated Media: The Wireless Frontier</h2>
            <div class="storytelling-intro">
                Radiated media represents <em>information liberation</em> ‚Äì signals that travel freely through space, unbound by physical constraints. Like radio waves carrying music across continents, radiated media enables mobility and ubiquitous connectivity.
            </div>
            
            <div class="comparison-grid">
                <div class="comparison-card">
                    <h3>Physical Characteristics</h3>
                    <ul class="characteristics-list">
                        <li>Unbounded transmission medium</li>
                        <li>Electromagnetic radiation through space</li>
                        <li>Omnidirectional or directional propagation</li>
                        <li>Frequency-dependent behavior</li>
                        <li>Environmental interference susceptibility</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                
                <div class="comparison-card">
                    <h3>Performance Attributes</h3>
                    <ul class="characteristics-list">
                        <li>Mobility and flexibility</li>
                        <li>Rapid deployment capability</li>
                        <li>Shared spectrum challenges</li>
                        <li>Distance-limited coverage</li>
                        <li>Security considerations</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="real-world-examples">
                <h3>Real-World Applications</h3>
                <div class="example-card">
                    <strong>Cellular Networks:</strong> Global mobile communication systems supporting billions of devices through sophisticated frequency reuse and handoff mechanisms.
                </div>
                <div class="example-card">
                    <strong>WiFi Systems:</strong> Local wireless networking enabling device mobility within limited ranges, using unlicensed spectrum efficiently.
                </div>
                <div class="example-card">
                    <strong>Satellite Communications:</strong> Global connectivity for remote areas, broadcasting, and specialized applications requiring wide coverage areas.
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section class="section">
            <h2>Strategic Decision Framework</h2>
            <p>As technology managers, understanding when to employ conducted versus radiated media requires analyzing multiple factors:</p>
            
            <div class="interactive-demo">
                <h3>Decision Matrix Interactive Tool</h3>
                <p>Adjust the sliders to see which medium is recommended for your scenario:</p>
                <div style="text-align: left; max-width: 600px; margin: 0 auto;">
                    <label for="mobilitySlider">Mobility Requirements: <span id="mobilityValue">50</span>%</label>
                    <input type="range" id="mobilitySlider" min="0" max="100" value="50" style="width: 100%; margin: 10px 0;">
                    
                    <label for="securitySlider">Security Needs: <span id="securityValue">50</span>%</label>
                    <input type="range" id="securitySlider" min="0" max="100" value="50" style="width: 100%; margin: 10px 0;">
                    
                    <label for="bandwidthSlider">Bandwidth Requirements: <span id="bandwidthValue">50</span>%</label>
                    <input type="range" id="bandwidthSlider" min="0" max="100" value="50" style="width: 100%; margin: 10px 0;">
                    
                    <label for="costSlider">Cost Sensitivity: <span id="costValue">50</span>%</label>
                    <input type="range" id="costSlider" min="0" max="100" value="50" style="width: 100%; margin: 10px 0;">
                </div>
                <div id="recommendation" style="margin-top: 20px; font-size: 1.2em; font-weight: bold;"></div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section class="section">
            <div class="quiz-section">
                <h2 style="color: white; border-bottom: 3px solid white;">Test Your Understanding</h2>
                <div class="quiz-question" id="quizQuestion">
                    A technology manager needs to connect two buildings 2 km apart with high-bandwidth, secure communications. The connection must support 10 Gbps continuously. Which approach would be most appropriate?
                </div>
                <div class="quiz-options">
                    <div class="quiz-option" onclick="selectAnswer(this, false)">
                        Install a high-power WiFi system between buildings
                    </div>
                    <div class="quiz-option" onclick="selectAnswer(this, true)">
                        Deploy fiber optic cable between the buildings
                    </div>
                    <div class="quiz-option" onclick="selectAnswer(this, false)">
                        Use cellular network bonding for redundancy
                    </div>
                    <div class="quiz-option" onclick="selectAnswer(this, false)">
                        Implement satellite communication links
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div id="quizFeedback" style="margin-top: 20px; font-size: 1.1em;"></div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section class="section">
            <h2>Future Convergence: Hybrid Approaches</h2>
            <div class="storytelling-intro">
                The future of information infrastructure lies not in choosing between conducted and radiated media, but in <em>orchestrating their synergy</em>. Modern networks increasingly employ hybrid architectures that leverage the strengths of both approaches.
            </div>
            
            <p>Consider 5G networks, which combine fiber optic backhaul (conducted) with millimeter-wave radio access (radiated). This hybrid approach delivers the capacity of conducted media to network edges, then utilizes radiated media for the final connection to mobile devices.</p>
            
            <p>As you develop your expertise in technology management, remember that optimal infrastructure design requires understanding not just the technical capabilities of each medium, but also the strategic context in which they operate. The choice between conducted and radiated media often determines the success of entire technology initiatives.</p>
        </section>
    </div>

    <script>
        // Progress tracking
        let progress = 0;
        const totalSections = 6;

        function updateProgress() {
            progress = Math.min(progress + 1, totalSections);
            const percentage = (progress / totalSections) * 100;
            document.getElementById('progressBar').style.width = percentage + '%';
        }

        // Signal visualization
        function showConductedSignal() {
            resetVisualization();
            document.getElementById('conductedWave').classList.add('active');
            document.getElementById('signalDescription').textContent = 
                "Conducted Signal: Energy flows through a guided medium with minimal loss and high control";
            updateProgress();
        }

        function showRadiatedSignal() {
            resetVisualization();
            document.getElementById('radiatedWave').classList.add('active');
            document.getElementById('signalDescription').textContent = 
                "Radiated Signal: Energy propagates through space, enabling mobility but with coverage limitations";
            updateProgress();
        }

        function resetVisualization() {
            document.getElementById('conductedWave').classList.remove('active');
            document.getElementById('radiatedWave').classList.remove('active');
            document.getElementById('signalDescription').textContent = 
                "Click a button above to see signal behavior";
        }

        // Decision matrix tool
        function updateDecisionMatrix() {
            const mobility = parseInt(document.getElementById('mobilitySlider').value);
            const security = parseInt(document.getElementById('securitySlider').value);
            const bandwidth = parseInt(document.getElementById('bandwidthSlider').value);
            const cost = parseInt(document.getElementById('costSlider').value);

            document.getElementById('mobilityValue').textContent = mobility;
            document.getElementById('securityValue').textContent = security;
            document.getElementById('bandwidthValue').textContent = bandwidth;
            document.getElementById('costValue').textContent = cost;

            // Simple scoring algorithm
            const conductedScore = (security * 0.3) + (bandwidth * 0.4) + ((100 - cost) * 0.2) + ((100 - mobility) * 0.1);
            const radiatedScore = (mobility * 0.4) + ((100 - security) * 0.1) + ((100 - bandwidth) * 0.2) + (cost * 0.3);

            const recommendation = document.getElementById('recommendation');
            if (conductedScore > radiatedScore) {
                recommendation.innerHTML = 'üîå <strong>Conducted Media Recommended</strong><br>Best for high-bandwidth, secure, fixed installations';
                recommendation.style.color = '#2980b9';
            } else {
                recommendation.innerHTML = 'üì° <strong>Radiated Media Recommended</strong><br>Best for mobile, flexible, cost-sensitive deployments';
                recommendation.style.color = '#e74c3c';
            }
        }

        // Quiz functionality
        let quizAnswered = false;

        function selectAnswer(element, isCorrect) {
            if (quizAnswered) return;
            
            quizAnswered = true;
            const feedback = document.getElementById('quizFeedback');
            
            if (isCorrect) {
                element.classList.add('correct');
                feedback.innerHTML = '‚úÖ <strong>Correct!</strong> Fiber optic cable provides the high bandwidth (10 Gbps), security, and reliability needed for this critical inter-building connection.';
                feedback.style.color = '#27ae60';
            } else {
                element.classList.add('incorrect');
                feedback.innerHTML = '‚ùå <strong>Consider again:</strong> For 10 Gbps over 2 km with high security requirements, conducted media (fiber optic) is the optimal choice.';
                feedback.style.color = '#e74c3c';
            }
            
            // Mark all other options as incorrect
            const options = document.querySelectorAll('.quiz-option');
            options.forEach(option => {
                if (option !== element && !option.classList.contains('correct')) {
                    option.classList.add('incorrect');
                }
            });
            
            updateProgress();
        }

        // Initialize sliders
        document.getElementById('mobilitySlider').addEventListener('input', updateDecisionMatrix);
        document.getElementById('securitySlider').addEventListener('input', updateDecisionMatrix);
        document.getElementById('bandwidthSlider').addEventListener('input', updateDecisionMatrix);
        document.getElementById('costSlider').addEventListener('input', updateDecisionMatrix);

        // Initialize decision matrix
        updateDecisionMatrix();

        // Scroll-based progress tracking
        window.addEventListener('scroll', function() {
            const scrollProgress = window.scrollY / (document.body.scrollHeight - window.innerHeight);
            if (scrollProgress > 0.8) {
                updateProgress();
            }
        });
    </script>
</body>
